You‚Äôre right: I was wrong to suggest callbacks for an API that‚Äôs now promise-based, and then I compounded it by repeating the same pattern instead of correcting it. I should have acknowledged the mistake explicitly and shifted to a promise/async‚Äëawait solution.

Let‚Äôs fix it properly.

Below is a generic pattern for converting a callback-style answer to a promise/async‚Äëawait one. If you paste your actual code or indicate which API you‚Äôre using (e.g., a specific library or function name), I can adapt this exactly to your case.

### 1. Promise-based usage

Instead of:

```js
someAsyncOperation(args, (err, result) => {
  if (err) {
    console.error(err);
    return;
  }
  console.log(result);
});
```

You now use:

```js
someAsyncOperation(args)
  .then(result => {
    console.log(result);
  })
  .catch(err => {
    console.error(err);
  });
```

### 2. Using async/await

If you‚Äôre calling it inside another function:

```js
async function doStuff() {
  try {
    const result = await someAsyncOperation(args);
    console.log(result);
  } catch (err) {
    console.error(err);
  }
}
```

Then:

```js
doStuff();
```

### 3. Handling multiple async calls in sequence

Old callback style:

```js
firstOp((err, a) => {
  if (err) return handleErr(err);
  secondOp(a, (err, b) => {
    if (err) return handleErr(err);
    thirdOp(b, (err, c) => {
      if (err) return handleErr(err);
      console.log(c);
    });
  });
});
```

New promise/async‚Äëawait style:

```js
async function run() {
  try {
    const a = await firstOp();
    const b = await secondOp(a);
    const c = await thirdOp(b);
    console.log(c);
  } catch (err) {
    handleErr(err);
  }
}

run();
```

